title: Thanos’ Curse
body:
Something to ponder on that I  have not seen floating around yet. Remember when Tony made Thanos bleed? When he did “all that for a drop of blood?”

Thanos touched his wound with the middle finger and his index finger. And shortly afterwards, Thanos drove the blade straight through Tony.

Thanos’ fist presses the blade hilt-deep into him. When grabbing a sword, one would instinctively put their thumb on one side, the other fingers on the other, and therefore the index finger would be closest to the victim. At this moment, Thanos’ blood is pressed against Tony’s open wound. Wouldn’t it be horrifying if, at this moment, Tony had become cursed not just by knowledge, but also through Thanos’ blood?

One of the main issues with Iron Man wielding the gauntlet in Endgame is that he would lack the strength to do so. But what if he “acquired” said ability? Thanos would have created the only person capable of undoing the snap. This is why he had to survive, why Strange handed over the time stone. The 1 in 14 million chance works in two stages:

  1. Ant-Man had to not be dusted, be stuck in the quantum realm and return to lead the Avengers into the multi-verse to acquire (alternate) infinity stones.
  2. Stark had to be wounded and infected with Thanos’ blood. Then he had to survive and return to Earth to later wield the acquired stones.

It sounds far-fetched, maybe, but how would anybody survive in space without food or water for four days? Well, if one was cursed with near immortality, I suppose. There’s also the matter of the wound that he received on Titan. The planet was covered in dust, and it certainly was not hygienic to lay on the ground like he did. Then he plastered the wound together with some nanites and called it a day, ignoring the fact that dirt must have gotten into that gruesome wound. Well, guess who is immune to disease and infections? Thanos. Guess whose wound doesn’t seem to cause any complications in Endgame? Tony’s.

So, what if Thanos had to create his own downfall, because in none of the other futures was any other person left standing able to wield the gauntlet? I am not saying that Tony must be the only one wielding it. Maybe it will be a joint effort. But it is quite possible that his additional strength will be needed to break this cycle. By accepting the time stone, Thanos sealed his fate: The transferral of blood became a set point in time. It just makes sense that one cannot rewind time back to before one received the stone, because then you would not be in possession of the stone to go further back.

summary: Learn Me Hard Oh, Learn Me Right
title: Learn Me Hard Oh, Learn Me Right
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2TEOKJZ

by AHM1121

“Have you always struggled with math, Steve?” Dr. Potts asked.

The blush crept higher as the same shame he had felt since the second grade crawl up his spine.

“You’re not the only one.” She assured, handing the papers back to him. “Luckily, you can get a one-on-one tutoring at the student center, your tuition covers two sessions per week.”

“Thank you ma’am.” Steve accepted the paper and stood, sliding his backpack over his shoulders. Making his way out of her office he paused when she called his name. “Ma’am?”

“Ask for Bucky Barnes.” Her lips turned up at the name. “He’s one of the math majors that I oversee, haven’t had a student work with him who hasn’t passed.”

No pressure, Steve thought. “I’ll make sure to do that. Thank you Dr. Potts.”
“Good luck Steve.”

He didn’t need luck, he needed a miracle.

“Have you always struggled with math, Steve?” Dr. Potts asked.

The blush crept higher as the same shame he had felt since the second grade crawl up his spine.

“You’re not the only one.” She assured, handing the papers back to him. “Luckily, you can get a one-on-one tutoring at the student center, your tuition covers two sessions per week.”

“Thank you ma’am.” Steve accepted the paper and stood, sliding his backpack over his shoulders. Making his way out of her office he paused when she called his name. “Ma’am?”

“Ask for Bucky Barnes.” Her lips turned up at the name. “He’s one of the math majors that I oversee, haven’t had a student work with him who hasn’t passed.”

No pressure, Steve thought. “I’ll make sure to do that. Thank you Dr. Potts.”
“Good luck Steve.”

He didn’t need luck, he needed a miracle.
